cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.CC, cs.DL. 

The paper deals with geometric problems, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The use of parameterized complexity theory and the focus on the dimensionality of the problems suggests that it could also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The W[1]-hardness results suggest that it could also belong to cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and the use of the Exponential Time Hypothesis suggests that it could also belong to cs.DL (Digital Libraries).
